# PostgresSaver Checkpointer

`PostgresSaver` is a drop-in replacement for `MemorySaver` that persists agent state to a PostgreSQL database. Checkpoints survive process restarts, enabling true cross-session conversation persistence.

## Package and install

```bash
npm install @langchain/langgraph-checkpoint-postgres pg
```

Peer dependencies `@langchain/core` and `@langchain/langgraph-checkpoint` are already in the tree via `@langchain/langgraph`.

## Initialization

### From connection string

```typescript
import { PostgresSaver } from "@langchain/langgraph-checkpoint-postgres";

const checkpointer = PostgresSaver.fromConnString(
  process.env.POSTGRES_URL ?? "postgresql://user:password@localhost:5432/langgraph",
);
await checkpointer.setup(); // auto-creates tables, idempotent
```

### From an existing pg.Pool

```typescript
import { PostgresSaver } from "@langchain/langgraph-checkpoint-postgres";
import pg from "pg";

const pool = new pg.Pool({ connectionString: process.env.POSTGRES_URL });
const checkpointer = new PostgresSaver(pool, undefined, { schema: "public" });
await checkpointer.setup();
```

## Connection string format

```
postgresql://user:password@host:port/database
```

Example: `postgresql://postgres:postgres@localhost:5432/langgraph`

## Table creation

`setup()` auto-creates all required tables and runs migrations. It is idempotent — safe to call on every startup. No manual DDL needed.

To use a custom Postgres schema (defaults to `public`):

```typescript
PostgresSaver.fromConnString("postgresql://...", { schema: "my_schema" });
```

## Swapping from MemorySaver

The only change is the checkpointer construction — everything else (`createDeepAgent`, `thread_id` config, `invoke`) stays identical:

```typescript
// Before (ephemeral)
import { MemorySaver } from "@langchain/langgraph";
const checkpointer = new MemorySaver();

// After (persistent)
import { PostgresSaver } from "@langchain/langgraph-checkpoint-postgres";
const checkpointer = PostgresSaver.fromConnString(process.env.POSTGRES_URL!);
await checkpointer.setup();
```

Both implement `BaseCheckpointSaver`, so the agent code is unaware of the backend.

## When to use

- Persistence across process restarts
- Multi-session agents that resume conversations
- Production deployments where state must not be lost
- When you want to inspect checkpoint data via Postico or psql

## Environment variable

Add to your `.env`:

```
POSTGRES_URL=postgresql://postgres:postgres@localhost:5432/langgraph
```

Make sure the database exists before the first run. `setup()` handles the tables but not database creation.
